**** Simplifying circuits with Karnaugh maps

***** Review and further reading

A logic gate is a component that receives some input bits and
produces an output bit that is defined by a Boolean operation.  The
value of the output bit is a function of the inputs, and can be
specified using a truth table.

Some of the logic gates correspond to the basic operators of Boolean
algebra.


- buf --- a buffer that outputs its input value
- inv --- inverter
- and2, and3, and4 --- logical and gates with 2, 3, 4 inputs
- or2, or3, or4
- xor2, xor3, xor4
- nand2, nand3, nand4
- nor2, nor3, nor5
- xnor2, xnor3, xnor4

***** lec05 Circuit Simulation
**** Circuit simulation

- Haskell notation
- Writing the circuit specification 
- Writing the simulation driver
- Test data 
- Running the simulation

***** Notes about Haskell

- Hydra is \emph{embedded} in Haskell

- Rather than learning the language from the ground up, it's
  better to
  
  - Study working examples
  - Run them
  - Modify them
  
***** Layout

- Layout --- indentation and line breaks --- is significant!
- In many languages you specify the structure twice
  
  - Using punctuation: braces, semicolons, begin/end, etc.
  - Using indentation
   
- In Haskell (and Hydra) you can use indentation to determine
  structure
  
  - It's simple, but the precise syntax rules are complex
  - Just follow the examples!
  - If you like you can use punctuation in Haskell, too
  
\begin{center}
  \fbox{\color{red}\large \textbf{Never use tabs.  Always use spaces
      for indentation.}}
\end{center}

***** Systematic design

- Decide whether you want a combinational or sequential circuit
  
  - Consider path depth (gate delay), complexity of circuit,
    whether problem takes variable amount of time
  
- Combinational: use synthesis from truth table, Boolean algebra,
  sum of cases, standard patterns (e.g. carry propagation)
- Sequential
  
  - Identify the state
  - Decide what you want to go into state at each tick
  - Design combinational logic to calculate these values
   
- Using building blocks
  
  - Introduce building block circuits, e.g. for each bit position
  - Design full circuit based on data dependencies
  - Design building block circuit with state and combinational
    logic
  
****** Design the circuit and test data

- Design the circuit systematically
- Work out some test data
- Small test data with expected results
- Sometimes it's also useful to have larger scale test data
- Tests should cover normal cases and boundary cases
  
- Write the simulation driver (follow the examples!)
- Run the simulation and compare its results with your predictions
***** Bidirectional shift register

The problem: design a shift register containing 4 bits, which can

- remember a 4-bit word 
- shift its contents to the left or to the right by 1 bit.

The behaviour is controlled by an opcode, which must be 2 bits

- 0 (00) -- no state change
- 1 (01) -- load input word x
- 2 (10) -- shift right
- 3 (11) -- shift left

****** Circuit specification
****** Circuit specification BSR4: bidirectional shift register

Consider state (a bit for each bit position in the word) and data
dependencies (each position needs an input bit from |x|, and an input
from the left and the right.

#+BEGIN_EXAMPLE
sr4 :: CBit a => (a,a) -> a -> a -> [a] -> (a,a,[a])
sr4 op li ri [x0,x1,x2,x3] = (y0, y3, [y0,y1,y2,y3])
  where
     y0 = srb op li y1 x0
     y1 = srb op y0 y2 x1
     y2 = srb op y1 y3 x2
     y3 = srb op y2 ri x3
#+END_EXAMPLE
OK TO HERE
**** What value do you want?
  
Work out what value you want to put in the |dff| --- it depends on the
op.

- In this bit position we have left input (li), right input (ri),
  and input bit from load word (x)
- nop (op=00) we want the old value in this bit position
- load (op=01) we want x
- shift right (op=10) we want left input li
- shift left (op=11) we want right input ri

Need to make a choice

- A mux1 uses a 1-bit control to choose from 2 inputs
- A mux2 uses a 2-bit control to choose from 4 inputs

****** Bit multiplexers
OK TO HERE
Bit multiplexer.  Output = if c=0 then x else y

#+BEGIN_EXAMPLE
mux1 :: Bit a => a -> a -> a -> a
mux1 c x y = 
  or2 (and2 (inv c) x) (and2 c y)
#+END_EXAMPLE

Use two control bits to select one of 4 alternatives:

#+BEGIN_EXAMPLE
mux2 :: Bit a => (a,a) -> a -> a -> a -> a -> a
mux2 (c0,c1) a b c d =
  mux1 c0 (mux1 c1 a b) (mux1 c1 c d)
#+END_EXAMPLE

**** Design of the shift register bit


srb :: CBit a => (a,a) -> a -> a -> a -> a
srb op li ri x = y
  where y = dff (mux2 op y x li ri)


- 0 (00) -- no state change
- 1 (01) -- load input word x
- 2 (10) -- shift right
- 3 (11) -- shift left

*** Simulation driver
*** Simulation driver BSR4run

- You can define the simulation driver in a separate file.
- The module Main contains the executable program.
- The Hydra system and the circuit need to be imported 
- The module BSR4 is defined in file BSR4.hs (or BSR4.lhs)

#+BEGIN_EXAMPLE
module Main where

import HDL.Hydra.Core.Lib
import BSR4
#+END_EXAMPLE
OK TO HERE
**** Optional: define a main program

- You can define several executable test cases with type |IO ()|
- Common convention: |main| is a main program that runs all the
  tests
- You can load the file into ghci and enter |main|
- You can compile to an executable which will run |main|
  automatically
- You can put a sequence of executable operations in a |do| block 
- |putStrLn "hello"| prints the string -- it's good practice to
  label parts of the output
- |runBSR4 test_data_1| means run the simulation driver on the
  data

#+BEGIN_EXAMPLE
#+BEGIN_EXAMPLE
main :: IO ()
main =
  do  putStrLn "Testing BSR4 on test_data_1"
      runBSR4 test_data_1
#+END_EXAMPLE
#+END_EXAMPLE

***** Simulation driver

- Important: be clear about what is software and what is hardware!
- A circuit specification describes hardware
- You can either fabricate the specification (you get hardware) or
  simulate it (using software)
- Even if you simulate the specification, the \emph{thing} that
  you're simulating is hardware
- To provide inputs to the simulated circuit, you need software: a
  simulation driver

****** Form of a simulation driver

- Function definition: arguments to the driver
- Input section: extract signals from readable inputs
- Circuit section: apply the circuit to its inputs, yielding its
  outputs
- Output section: format the output signals to produce text

****** Complete simulation driver for bsr4 circuit
OK TO HERE

#+BEGIN_EXAMPLE
#+BEGIN_EXAMPLE
runBSR4 :: [[Int]] -> IO ()
runBSR4 input = runAllInput input output
  where
-- Extract input signals from the input data
    op = getbit2  input 0
    l  = getbit   input 1
    r  = getbit   input 2
    x  = getbin 4 input 3
-- Connect the inputs and output signals to the circuit
    (lo,ro,y) = sr4 op l r x
-- Format the output signals
    output =
      [string "op=", bit (fst op), bit (snd op),
       string " l=", bit l,
       string " r=", bit r,
       string " x=", hex x,
       string "   Output lo=", bit lo,
       string " ro=", bit ro,
       string " y=", hex y]
#+END_EXAMPLE
#+END_EXAMPLE

****** Parts of a simulation driver

- Type and top level equation, then |where|
- Extract input signals from the input data
  
  - One equation for each input, for example
  - |op = getbit2 input 0| --- |op| is a pair of bits, from column 0
  - |li = getbit input 1|  --- |li| is a bit from column 1
  - |x = getbin 4 input 3| --- |x| is 4-bit binary from column 3
  
- Connect the inputs and outputs to the circuit
  
  - One equation, e.g. |(lo,ro,y) = sr4 op li ri x|
  
- Format the output signals: list of format specifiers

  - string "x=" --- literal string to label signals 
  - |bit li| --- format the |li| bit signal as 0 or 1 
  - |hex x| --- format the word |x| as hexadecimal
  
****** Test data
PROBLEM BEFORE THIS POINT
- Test data is a list of lists of numbers
  
  - Each sublist provides inputs for one clock cycle
  - Lay out the data neatly with column headings
  - Good practice: include the expected output y
  
- Designing good test data
  
  - Include some normal cases
  - Include some boundary cases
  - Don't just use trivial data, but also don't just use
    exceptional data
  - {\color{red} Would you trust a system that has been tested
    with the data that you provide?}
  - {\color{red} If you're the customer, would you accept the
    product from an engineer based on this test data?}
  
****** Define some test data for BSR4

#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
testdata :: [[Int]]
testdata =
-----------------------------------
--  op l  r   x        op      y
-----------------------------------
  [[1, 0, 0,  9],  -- load 9   0
   [0, 0, 0,  0],  -- nop      9
   [3, 0, 0,  0],  -- shl 0    9
   [3, 0, 1,  0],  -- shl 1    2
   [0, 0, 0,  0],  -- nop      5
   [1, 0, 0,  4],  -- load 4   5
   [2, 1, 0,  0],  -- shr 1    4
   [2, 0, 0,  0],  -- shr 0    a
   [2, 0, 0,  0],  -- shr 0    5
   [2, 1, 0,  0],  -- shr 1    2
   [0, 0, 0,  0]]  -- nop      9
#+END_SRC

****** Run the simulation

#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
$ ghc -e main BSR4Run
op=01 l=0 r=0 x=9   Output lo=0 ro=0 y=0
op=00 l=0 r=0 x=0   Output lo=1 ro=1 y=9
op=11 l=0 r=0 x=0   Output lo=1 ro=1 y=9
op=11 l=0 r=1 x=0   Output lo=0 ro=0 y=2
op=00 l=0 r=0 x=0   Output lo=0 ro=1 y=5
op=01 l=0 r=0 x=4   Output lo=0 ro=1 y=5
op=10 l=1 r=0 x=0   Output lo=0 ro=0 y=4
op=10 l=0 r=0 x=0   Output lo=1 ro=0 y=a
op=10 l=0 r=0 x=0   Output lo=0 ro=1 y=5
op=10 l=1 r=0 x=0   Output lo=0 ro=0 y=2
op=00 l=0 r=0 x=0   Output lo=1 ro=1 y=9
$
#+END_SRC

