BEGIN EXERCISE
Suppose \texttt{x = [x0,x1,x2]}, \texttt{y = [y0,y1,y2,y3]}, and
  \texttt{z = x++y}.  What are the values of \texttt{z},
  \texttt{length z}, and \texttt{z!!4}?
BEGIN SOLUTION
#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
z = [x0, x1, x2, y0, y1, y2, y3]
length z = 7
z !! 4 = y1
#+END_SRC
END SOLUTION
END EXERCISE

BEGIN EXERCISE
A circuit has the type declaration \texttt{circ :: Signal a => a
    -> (a,a) -> [a] -> (a,[a])}.  How many groups of input bits are
  there?  How are they structured?  How is the output structured?
BEGIN SOLUTION
There are three arrows in the type, so there are three groups of
input bits.  The first is a singleton bit; the second is a pair of
bits; the third is a word of bits.  The output is a pair consisting
of a singleton bit and a word of bits.
END SOLUTION
END EXERCISE

BEGIN EXERCISE
Modify the definition of \texttt{rippleAdd4} to handle 6-bit
  words.
BEGIN SOLUTION
This can be done manually by following the pattern used in
|rippleAdd4|:
#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
rippleAdd6 :: Signal a => a -> [(a,a)] -> (a,[a])
rippleAdd6 cin [(x0,y0),(x1,y1),(x2,y2),(x3,y3),(x4,y4),(x5,y5)]
  = (c0, [s0,s1,s2,s3,s4,s5])
  where
    (c0,s0) = fullAdd (x0,y0) c1
    (c1,s1) = fullAdd (x1,y1) c2
    (c2,s2) = fullAdd (x2,y2) c3
    (c3,s3) = fullAdd (x3,y3) c4
    (c4,s4) = fullAdd (x4,y4) c5
    (c5,s5) = fullAdd (x5,y5) cin
#+END_SRC
Of course, a more elegant way is simply to use the general
\texttt{rippleAdd}, which works for all word sizes, including 6-bit
words:
#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
rippleAdd6 = rippleAdd
#+END_SRC
In reality, there is little point in defining \texttt{rippleAdd6}, as
you can just use \texttt{rippleAdd} anyway.
END SOLUTION
END EXERCISE

BEGIN EXERCISE
Define an 8-bit adder, named |rippleAdd8|.  Don't follow the
  pattern of \texttt{rippleAdd4}, with eight equations.  Instead, use
  \texttt{rippleAdd4} as a building block circuit.  In your definition
  of \texttt{rippleAdd8}, use two separate internal
  \texttt{rippleAdd4} circuits, and connect them up appropriately.
BEGIN SOLUTION
As noted above, we could just define \texttt{rippleAdd8 = rippleAdd},
or extend the lengthy manual definition to contain 8 equations.
However, this problem is not actually pointless: in some technologies
(e.g. the SSI chip family), you may have a \texttt{rippleAdd4}
primitive, and you really want the solution to contain just two chips.
The point of this problem is handling the carries properly.
#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
rippleAdd8 cin [(x0,y0),(x1,y1),(x2,y2),(x3,y3),
                (x4,y4),(x5,y5),(x6,y6),(x7,y7)]
  = (cout, [s0,s1,s2,s3,s4,s5,s6,s7]
  where  (cout, [s0,s1,s2,s3])
            = rippleAdd4 cc [(x0,y0),(x1,y1),(x2,y2),(x3,y3)]
         (c, [s4,s5,s6,s7])
            = rippleAdd4 cin [(x4,y4),(x5,y5),(x6,y6),(x7,y7)]
#+END_SRC
This solution is still awfully tedious, as it mentions all the signals
explicitly.  It could be shortened a bit, using some of Hydra's
operators on words, but if you have to design using SSI or MSI
components you will be stuck with tedious designs that don't scale
well.  Usually you're better off with building block circuits
(\texttt{reg1}, \texttt{mux1}, \texttt{fullAdd}, and the rest) along
with design patterns.
END SOLUTION
END EXERCISE

BEGIN EXERCISE
Use Hydra to similate the \texttt{and2} and \texttt{xor3} logic
  gates, and print their truth tables.
BEGIN SOLUTION
