}
\end{solution}
\end{exercise}



\begin{exercise}
We have two word signals |x| and |y|, which have the same
  word size (but we don't know or care exactly what the size is).
  There is a single control bit |c|.  Define a signal |z| which is
  a word; on each clock cycle, |z| is the same as |x| if |c=0|
  during that cycle, but |z| is the same as |y| if |c=1|.
\begin{solution}

#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
z = mux1w c x y
#+END_SRC
\end{solution}
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
Study the |BSR4| example circuit and its test bench (download
  these from the Moodle page).  Work out your predicted outputs
  from the circuit, given the input values that are provided.  Then
  run the simulation, and compare the simulated outputs with your
  predictions.
\begin{solution}

To simulate a sequential circuit, build a simulation table with a
row for each clock cycle, and a column for each signal.  The top
row is for cycle 0, and you should initialize all the flip flop
output signals to 0 (or to ?).  For each cycle, fill in the values
of the input signal columns.  Then work out the combinational
signals by simulating the logic gates.  When you're finished with
that, the entire row will be filled in.

Once a row has been completely filled in, you have simulated the
signals reaching validity during a clock cycle.

The cycle ends with a clock tick.  To simulate the clock tick, copy
the values of the signals that are input to a flip flop in the
current row to the corresponding flip flop output signal in the row
below.  Do this for all the flip flops.  Also, put the values of
the circuit's input signals into the corresponding columns of the
new row.

Keep going, a row at a time, until you want to stop the simulation.

The essential point of this problem is to get the timing right.
During a clock cycle the logic gates are calculating the inputs to
the registers; those inputs won't actually enter the register until
the clock tick (which is in the future) and you won't be able to
observe the new state of the register until the next clock cycle
(which is even farther into the future).  For example, if a shift
register contains 1000 and you have an opcode that says to shift to
the right with a left input of 1, the \emph{current} register
readout is 1000, but on the \emph{next} cycle the register will
output 1100.  A common error is to think that the future
event---the execution of the shift operation---has already
happened.

Here is the file BSR4.hs which defines the circuit:

{\small
#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
module BSR4 where

import HDL.Hydra.Core.Lib
import HDL.Hydra.Circuits.StandardCircuits

-- Meaning of op:
--     0 -- no state change
--     1 -- load input word x
--     2 -- shift right
--     3 -- shift left

sr4 :: Clocked a => (a,a) -> a -> a -> [a] -> [a]
sr4 op l r [x0,x1,x2,x3] = [y0,y1,y2,y3]
  where
     y0 = srb op l  y1 x0
     y1 = srb op y0 y2 x1
     y2 = srb op y1 y3 x2
     y3 = srb op y2 r  x3

sr :: Clocked a => (a,a) -> a -> a -> [a] -> (a,a,[a])
sr op l r xs = mscan (srb' op) l r xs
  where srb' a b c d = fanout3 (srb a b c d)

srb :: Clocked a => (a,a) -> a -> a -> a -> a
srb op l r x = y
  where y = dff (mux2 op y x l r)
#+END_SRC
}

This is the testbench, TestBSR4.hs:

{\small
#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
module Main where

import HDL.Hydra.Core.Lib

import BSR4

main :: IO ()
main = runBSR4 test_data_1

-- 0   no operation
-- 1   load input word x
-- 2   shift right
-- 3   shift left

runBSR4 :: [[Int]] -> IO ()
runBSR4 input =
  do putStrLn "\nBSR4 circuit"
     runAllInput input output
  where
    op = getbit2  input 0
    l  = getbit   input 1
    r  = getbit   input 2
    x  = getbin 4 input 3
    y = sr4 op l r x
    output =
      [string "op=", bit (fst op), bit (snd op),
       string " l=", bit l,
       string " r=", bit r,
       string " x=", hex x,
       string "  output y=", hex y]

test_data_1 :: [[Int]]
test_data_1 =
-----------------------------------
--  op l  r   x        op      y
-----------------------------------
  [[1, 0, 0,  9],  -- load 9   0
   [0, 0, 0,  0],  -- nop      9
   [3, 0, 0,  0],  -- shl 0    9
   [3, 0, 1,  0],  -- shl 1    2
   [0, 0, 0,  0],  -- nop      5
   [1, 0, 0,  4],  -- load 4   5
   [2, 1, 0,  0],  -- shr 1    4
   [2, 0, 0,  0],  -- shr 0    a
   [2, 0, 0,  0],  -- shr 0    5
   [2, 1, 0,  0],  -- shr 1    2
   [0, 0, 0,  0]]  -- nop      9
#+END_SRC
}

Here is the output from running the simulation:

{\small
#+BEGIN_SRC sigma
*Main> main

BSR4 circuit
op=01 l=0 r=0 x=9  output y=0
op=00 l=0 r=0 x=0  output y=9
op=11 l=0 r=0 x=0  output y=9
op=11 l=0 r=1 x=0  output y=2
op=00 l=0 r=0 x=0  output y=5
op=01 l=0 r=0 x=4  output y=5
op=10 l=1 r=0 x=0  output y=4
op=10 l=0 r=0 x=0  output y=a
op=10 l=0 r=0 x=0  output y=5
op=10 l=1 r=0 x=0  output y=2
op=00 l=0 r=0 x=0  output y=9
*Main> 
#+END_SRC
}
\end{solution}
\end{exercise}


\subsection{Adding words}

A 4-Bit Ripple Carry Adder

\vspace{1em}
\begin{center}
  \includegraphics[angle=0,scale=0.45]{figures/xfig/rippleAdd4.eps}
\end{center}

\begin{verbatim}
rippleAdd4 :: Signal a => a -> [(a,a)] -> [a]
rippleAdd4 cin [(x0,y0), (x1,y1), (x2,y2), (x3,y3)] = [c0,s0,s1,s2,s3]
  where
    (c0,s0) = fullAdd (x0,y0) c1
    (c1,s1) = fullAdd (x1,y1) c2
    (c2,s2) = fullAdd (x2,y2) c3
    (c3,s3) = fullAdd (x3,y3) cin
\end{verbatim}

Ripple carry adder schematic

\begin{center}
  \includegraphics[angle=0,scale=0.5]{figures/xfig/rippleAdd4.eps}
\end{center}

Ripple carry adder specification

\begin{verbatim}
rippleAdd :: Signal a => a -> [(a,a)] -> (a,[a])
\end{verbatim}

The input words need to be in bit slice form:

\begin{verbatim}
xys = [(x0,y0), (x1,y1), (x2,y2), ..., ]
\end{verbatim}

\begin{verbatim}
rippleAdd4 :: Signal a => a -> [(a,a)] -> (a,[a])
rippleAdd4 cin [(x0,y0),(x1,y1),(x2,y2),(x3,y3)]
  = (c0, [s0,s1,s2,s3])
  where
    (c0,s0) = fullAdd (x0,y0) c1
    (c1,s1) = fullAdd (x1,y1) c2
    (c2,s2) = fullAdd (x2,y2) c3
    (c3,s3) = fullAdd (x3,y3) cin
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Bit slice organisation}

\begin{itemize}
\item Sometimes you have separate words, say \texttt{x :: [a]} and
  \texttt{y :: [a]}.
\item Sometimes you need to reorganise the signals into bit slice
  form, say \texttt{xy :: [(a,a)]}
\item This is done by \emph{wiring patterns}
\item Wiring patterns are implemented at circuit generation time;
  they don't involve any components, but just rearrange the wires.
\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
bitslice2 :: [a] -> [a] -> [(a,a)]
unbitslice2 :: [(a,b)] -> ([a], [b])
\end{verbatim}

For example, suppose you want to add \texttt{x} and \texttt{y},
with a carry input of 0.

\begin{verbatim}
(cout,sum) = rippleAdd cin (bitslice2 x y)
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Generating adders of arbitrary size}

\begin{itemize}
\item The \texttt{rippleAdd} circuit is similar to
  \texttt{rippleAdd4}, except it works on all word sizes.
\item At circuit generation time, \texttt{rippleAdd4} measures the
  sizes of its input words, and then it constructs a circuit with
  the right number of full adders.
\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
(c,ss) = rippleAdd cin xys
\end{verbatim}

Circuit generators

\begin{itemize}
\item Often we won't describe every component ``by hand''
\item We can use \emph{circuit generators} --- algorithms that
  create the circuit
\item The simplest kind is a \emph{generic circuit} which works for
  any word size
  \begin{itemize}
  \item rippleAdd4 is a 4-bit ripple carry adder
  \item rippleAdd is a generic $n$-bit ripple carry adder: it works
    for \emph{every word size}
  \item The circuit generator works by (1) measuring the size of
    the input word and (2) generating the required number of components
  \item This is not software to do the operation --- it
    is still a real circuit.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{How to subtract with an adder}

\begin{itemize}
\item There is a distinct ripple-borrow subtractor circuit
\item This isn't used much in real computers; it is much better
  to use the adder to do subtractions
\item Use these facts:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item A binary adder will get the right answer for both binary
    numbers and two's complement numbers
  \item In two's complement, to negate a number you (1) invert
    all the bits and (2) add one
  \item $x - y = x + (-y) = x + inv y + 1$
  \item The ripple carry adder doesn't just add two words; it
    also adds the carry input!
  \end{itemize}
\item To subtract \(x-y\), put x into one word input of the adder,
  put y with all its bits inverted into the other input, and set
  the carry input to 1
\end{itemize}


